"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997729","Wales Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales is not an employer in its own right. The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) provide employment services on our behalf. MoJ staff are based in either our London or Cardiff offices. No MoJ staff in the Department are paid at a rate below £8.75 per hour and no MoJ staff based in our London office are paid at a rate below £10.20 per hour.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","185772","2018-11-07T13:55:14.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997729/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997729/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-10-30","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997730","Scotland Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Office of the Secretary of Scotland does not employ staff directly. All staff that join do so on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government, who remain the employers.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","185773 ; 185793","2018-11-06T15:27:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997730/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997730/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-10-30","Scotland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997731","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>I can confirm that no members of staff in the Northern Ireland Office are paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-11-01T15:45:06.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997731/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997731/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-10-30","Northern Ireland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997732","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-07","<p>All MoJ employees are paid at least the National Minimum Wage and the National Living Wage.</p><p>1479 staff employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ HQ, HMCTS, LAA, OPG and CICA) and 543 by HMPPS are paid at a rate below £8.75 per hour.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-11-07T17:16:07.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997732/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997732/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-30","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997733","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>None of the Department's directly-employed staff are currently paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-11-06T11:23:31.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997733/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997733/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997734","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) pays over and above the National Living Wage, which was increased to £7.83 per hour in April 2018. The MOD has not formally signed up to the Living Wage Rates of £8.75 (National) and £10.20 (London), as defined by the Living Wage Foundation. In 2015 the then Secretary of State for Defence agreed that all London-based staff should be paid at least the equivalent of the Living Wage Foundation's London Living Wage rate. The MOD continues to pay above that rate.</p><p>As at 31 October 2018, a total of 9,965 MOD civilian staff were paid less than £10.20 per hour, of which a total of 1,757 were paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","185777","2018-11-05T17:07:51.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997734/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997734/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-30","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997735","Home Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>From April 2018, all employers in the UK were required to pay a new National Living Wage of £7.83 per hour. The Home Office pays all direct employees at least the statutory National Living Wage, regardless of age.</p><p>There are 103 direct employees (all apprentices) of the Home Office who earn less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-11-07T15:01:47.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997735/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997735/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Home Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997736","Treasury","false","2018-11-07","<p>No staff in HM Treasury are paid less than £8.75 per hour</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-11-07T16:31:03.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997736/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997736/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997737","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-02","<p>No UK-Based staff employed by the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office are paid less than the Real Living Wage rate of £8.75 per hour.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-02T16:34:00.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997737/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997737/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997738","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>On 31 October 2018, no individuals employed by the Department were paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-06T16:59:24.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997738/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997738/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Department of Health and Social Care: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997739","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions pays all employees at least the statutory National Living Wage of £7.83 per hour, regardless of age.</p><p> </p><p>The Living Wage Foundation advocates employers paying an alternative hourly rate known as the Real Living Wage (RLW) or London Living Wage (LLW). The current Real Living Wage is £8.75.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the working hours calculation used by the Living Wage Foundation DWP paid no employees less than £8.75 per hour as at September 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Please note this figure excludes employees on long term unpaid breaks, such as carer’s leave.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-07T10:23:03.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997739/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997739/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff in her Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997740","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-07","<p>The table below shows the number of staff (expressed as a headcount) paid below £8.75 for DfT(c) and its Agencies, as at 31 July 2018. The figures provided cover staff in all locations within the UK.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong> <strong>Below £</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfT(c)</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2,551</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driving Vehicle &amp; Standards Agency</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4,758</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver &amp; Vehicle Licensing Agency</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>6,013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1,134</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle Certification Agency</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>178</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-11-07T16:39:48.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997740/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-30","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997741","Department for International Trade","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for International Trade does not have any UK staff paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p><p> </p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-11-07T11:19:00.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997741/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997741/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-30","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997742","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-08","<p>When placing contracts through a competitive procurement process the Ministry of Defence (MOD) relies on competitive pressures to restrict profit margins to market rates. Such market pressure is absent in non-competitive contracting where the MOD relies instead upon the protections offered by Part 2 of the Defence Reform Act 2014 (DRA) and the Single Source Contract Regulations 2014 (SSCR).</p><p>Under the DRA and SSCR the MOD can make deductions to the profit margin earned on a Qualifying Defence Contract or Qualifying Subcontract, where that profit margin exceeds levels set out in the legislation.</p><p>In both competitive and single source contracting, the MOD can negotiate with a contractor Key Performance Incentives and Liquidated Damage provisions. These will have the effect of reducing payments, and hence profit margins, when performance is not to the agreed level.</p><p>MOD policy is not to pay suppliers for the costs of their failed bids. In a non-competitive procurement the MOD may consider payment of bid costs if it is the MOD that stops the tender process, at no fault of the supplier.</p><p>The MOD will have regard to the Single Source Regulations Office 'Statutory Guidance on Allowable Costs', when considering what if any business-related costs it is appropriate for the Department to accept into contract prices.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-11-08T14:28:11.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997742/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997742/answer","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997742/answer/previousversion/83796","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-30","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what deductions from profit margins are permissible under MOD contracts; and what steps the Government is taking to ensure that there are no costs to the public purse from failed bids and other business related costs.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","185720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997743","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-11-07","<p>I can confirm that all staff directly employed by the Department for Exiting the European Union are paid more than £8.75 per hour. All staff are paid above the living wage, as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-11-07T14:35:56.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997743/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997743/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-30","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997744","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-07","<p>There are no staff in the Department paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-11-07T11:30:43.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997744/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997744/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-30","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997745","Home Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Government has made a strong case for an ambitious and mutually beneficial future partnership with the EU that covers: mechanisms for rapid and secure data exchange, practical measures to support cross-border operational cooperation, and continued UK cooperation with EU law enforcement and criminal justice agencies.</p><p>Negotiations on the future relationship between the UK and the EU in the area of criminal justice and law enforcement cooperation is ongoing so we cannot pre-judge the outcome, but at this stage there is no reason to expect that differences in the definition of serious crime will be an issue.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-11-07T15:22:21.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997745/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997745/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of the effect of any differences in the definition of serious crime would have on (a) criminal justice and (b) police cooperation between the EU and the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","185664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997746","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>Cabinet Office moved to a new shared service platform in May 2017, which required a significant volume of complex data transfer between the old and new platforms. A number of issues were identified which called into question the accuracy of payment performance data, so the Department suspended prompt payment reporting until assured data was available. This has now been achieved, and we plan to publish the outstanding data shortly.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-11-06T14:37:04.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997746/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997746/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Government Departments: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reason his Department has not published the data on Cabinet Office prompt payment for (a) the third and second quarter of the 2017-2018 financial year and (b) the first and second quarter of the 2018-2019 financial year under procurement policy.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","185519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997747","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-07","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-11-07T17:17:10.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997747/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997747/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-30","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department applied pay protection (a) as a reasonable adjustment, (b) for welfare reasons, (c) as part of an agreed retirement plan and (d) for other reasons to employees who voluntarily downgraded in the three years up to to 3 July 2017; and for what reason his Department declined pay protection for such employees during that period.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","185604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997748","Department for Education","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for Education and its executive agencies do not have any employees who earn less than £8.75 per hour. There are 101 employees based outside of London who earn less than £10.20 per hour.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","185787","2018-11-07T17:28:56.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997748/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997748/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-30","Department for Education: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997749","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Rough Sleeping Initiative (RSI) is made up of a team of rough sleeping and homelessness experts, drawn from government departments, local authorities and agencies with specialist knowledge. These advisers have been working closely with local authorities with the highest numbers of rough sleepers, who are using our £30 million targeted fund to tackle rough sleeping in their area. The RSI has already made significant progress. According to data submitted by the local authorities, almost 3,500 individuals have so far been relieved or prevented from rough sleeping as a result of the RSI funding.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-06T10:49:11.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997749/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997749/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's press release New government initiative to reduce rough sleeping, published on 30 March 2018, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Rough Sleeping Team announced in that press release.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997750","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>No staff in the Department are paid below £8.75 per hour.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-11-07T11:59:35.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997750/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997750/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-30","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997751","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>During the process of formulating the Rough Sleeping Strategy, we engaged with the National Housing Federation and many other specialist organisations regarding move-on accommodation. Following this engagement and the release of the Strategy, we are implementing the Rapid Rehousing Pathway, of which the Supported Lettings Fund is a key element. This fund will help increase access to move-on accommodation by supporting those who require tenancy sustainment support, as well as build trust amongst landlords.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-06T10:49:51.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997751/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997751/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's press release entitled New government initiative to reduce rough sleeping, published on 30 March 2018, what progress the Government has made on its work with the National Housing Federation to look at providing additional, coordinated move-on accommodation for rough sleepers across the country.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997752","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-05","<p>Every member of staff employed by the Department is paid more than £8.75 per hour for their contracted hours.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-11-05T16:33:02.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997752/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997752/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-30","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997753","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>In my Department, no staff working outside London are paid less than UK Living Wage of £8.75 per hour and no staff working in London are paid less than the London Living Wage of £10.20 per hour.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-06T15:07:01.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997753/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997753/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997754","Attorney General","false","2018-11-07","<p>Neither the Attorney General’s Office, nor its superintended departments (the Crown Prosecution Service, the Serious Fraud Office, the Government Legal Department and HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate) have any staff paid below £8.75 an hour.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-11-07T10:25:34.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997754/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997754/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-10-30","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £8.75 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997755","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Cabinet Office is currently leading work with the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport to implement a package of measures for the future of social value and procurement, as set out in Government’s Civil Society Strategy. This includes training for government commercial staff to ensure that all major procurements in central government explicitly evaluate and report on their social value. Further information will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>This is an extension of the application of the Social Value Act across central government departments, rather than legislative changes to the Act itself.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-06T14:54:45.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997755/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997755/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to this Department's press release entitled Government announces major changes to rebuild trust after Carillion, published on 25 June 2018, what progress he has made on reforming the Public Services Public Services )(Social Value) Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","185520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997756","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>This Government is committed to improving perinatal mental health services for women during pregnancy and in the first postnatal year, so that women are able to access the right care at the right time and close to home.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is investing £365 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in perinatal mental health services, and NHS England is leading a transformation programme to ensure that by 2020/21 at least 30,000 more women each year are able to access evidence-based specialist mental health care during the perinatal period.</p><p> </p><p>General practitioners and primary care teams have a crucial role in supporting the identification and treatment of perinatal mental illness, including post-natal depression, and are part of an integrated pathway of services.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","185589","2018-11-06T11:15:02.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997756/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997756/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Postnatal Depression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to improve (a) early diagnosis and (b) support for mothers experiencing postnatal depression.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","185588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997757","Wales Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales is not an employer in its own right. The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) provide employment services on our behalf. MoJ staff are based in either our London or Cardiff offices. No MoJ staff in the Department are paid at a rate below £8.75 per hour and no MoJ staff based in our London office are paid at a rate below £10.20 per hour.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","185752","2018-11-07T13:55:14.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997757/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997757/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-10-30","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997758","Scotland Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Office of the Secretary of Scotland does not employ staff directly. All staff that join do so on assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government, who remain the employers.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","185753 ; 185793","2018-11-06T15:27:36.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997758/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997758/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-10-30","Scotland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997759","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>The household debt-to-income ratio has stabilised over the past year and was 140% in Q2 2018, down from a high of 160% in Q1 2008. Almost three quarters of household debt is secured against housing. Unsecured debt as a share of household income is now 35% (Q2 2018), down from its peak of 41% before the financial crisis (Q1 2007).</p><p> </p><p>Although the level of consumer credit remains high, when adjusted for inflation, the level of outstanding consumer credit stands 17.7% below its January 2008 peak.</p><p> </p><p>The Budget 2018 announced new policies to help households manage unexpected costs by increasing access to fair and affordable credit, as well as a consultation on a breathing space scheme for people who fall into problem debt.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-11-05T15:15:05.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997759/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997759/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of trends in the level of personal debt over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","185630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997760","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>This Government is committed to improving perinatal mental health services for women during pregnancy and in the first postnatal year, so that women are able to access the right care at the right time and close to home.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is investing £365 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in perinatal mental health services, and NHS England is leading a transformation programme to ensure that by 2020/21 at least 30,000 more women each year are able to access evidence-based specialist mental health care during the perinatal period.</p><p> </p><p>General practitioners and primary care teams have a crucial role in supporting the identification and treatment of perinatal mental illness, including post-natal depression, and are part of an integrated pathway of services.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","185588","2018-11-06T11:15:02.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997760/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997760/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Postnatal Depression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to improve (a) early diagnosis and (b) intervention for mothers experiencing postnatal depression.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","185589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997761","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>We regularly discuss this issue with Palestinian Authority representatives. I visited Khan al-Ahmar on 30 May, and on 12 June issued a video message emphasising the UK’s concern at the village’s imminent demolition. Our Consul General in Jerusalem most recently visited on 11 September to assess the situation on the ground and demonstrate UK support for the community. Officials from the Consulate-General in Jerusalem visited the community again on 1 October.</p><p>Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv have repeatedly raised our concerns about demolitions with Israeli Ministers and senior officials, and urged them to cease the counter-productive policy of demolitions, and provide a clear, transparent route to construction for Palestinians in Area C.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-05T13:24:56.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997761/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997761/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","Israel: Bedouin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has held with the Palestinian Authority on the planned demolition of the Palestinian village of Khan al-Ahmar.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","185494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-12-20","<p>We are not currently migrating any claimants from legacy benefits to Universal Credit. Claimants only move from existing benefits to Universal Credit through natural migration when they experience a significant change in their circumstances that triggers a new claim to benefit. Their entitlement is then calculated on the rules of their new benefit. This is a long-established principle which we maintain for Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>Subject to Parliamentary approval of the Managed Migration regulations, we will be spending £3.1 billion on transitional protections to ensure that no one loses out at the point of transition. This includes those currently receiving Severe Disability Premium (SDP). These regulations will prevent these claimants from moving over before the managed migration process, and provide financial protection for those who have already moved over.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold data on all disabled people receiving all disability premiums that have moved onto Universal Credit; however, published data shows that of the 42,000 people who were on Employment Support Allowance (ESA) and started a claim on Universal Credit Full Service within one month of closing their claim between May 2015 and February 2018, 15,000 were on ESA (Income Related) with Enhanced Disability Premium (EDP) and/or SDP. Of those, 1,000 were in receipt of SDP only, 11,000 in receipt of EDP only and 3,000 in receipt of EDP and SDP.</p><p> </p><p>This is published here:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/714479/ad-hoc-statistics-income-related-employment-and-support-allowance-february-2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/714479/ad-hoc-statistics-income-related-employment-and-support-allowance-february-2018.pdf</a></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-12-20T12:03:36.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997762/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997762/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997762/answer/previousversion/83317","Biography information for Sarah Newton","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-30","Universal Credit: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has made an estimate of the number of disabled people who previously received a disability premium that have been migrated onto universal credit without transitional protections.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","185631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997763","Home Office","false","2018-11-05","<p><br>Information on the number of visit visa application outcomes (grants, refusals, withdrawn and lapsed cases) is published in the quarterly Immigration Statistics, Visas volume 1 table vi_01_q, latest edition at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2018/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2018/list-of-tables#visas</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-05T17:08:35.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997763/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997763/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 29 October 2018 to Question 183507 on Visas: Tourism, what information his Department holds on the number of visitor visa requests that have been refused in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","185632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997764","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>Since January 2011, details of central government contracts, above the value of £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p><p>Contract award notices must include the SME status of the winning supplier, in accordance with Procurement Policy Note 07/16.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-06T14:58:17.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997764/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997764/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Government Departments: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many SMEs were awarded government contracts in the 2017-2018 financial year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","185521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997765","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-05","<p>All colleagues within DWP are required to understand, comply with and take appropriate action when dealing with individuals who may need additional support to enable them to access DWP Benefits and use our services. Guidance is clearly signposted within Cross Benefit Operational Instructions and is also available to front line operational colleagues through training programmes, Mental Health First Aiders (within ESA product lines) and within Customer Service A-Z instructions that are available to Telephony officers and staff within front line operational processing centres within the Working age Directorate. In addition, where an officer of the DWP is concerned that a customer has declared or may declare an intention to harm or kill themselves, the DWP has a specific action plan in place across the Working Age Directorate that supports the member of staff to understand their role in dealing with such threats.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-05T17:07:10.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997765/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997765/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-30","Social Security Benefits: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 26 October 2018 to Question 182841 on Social Security Benefits: Mental Health, what the safeguards are that were referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","185633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997766","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-11-01","<p>I can confirm that in London no members of Northern Ireland Office staff are paid less than the London Living Wage of £10.20 per hour. Staff members of the department working outside London are not paid less than the UK Living Wage.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-11-01T15:47:41.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997766/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997766/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-10-30","Northern Ireland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff in her Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997767","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>The rough sleeping counts or estimates take place between 1 October and 30 November.</p><p>Local authorities have to submit their data using the MHCLG DELTA online system by 14 December.</p><p>4 local authorities to date have submitted their data using this system. Once figures are submitted they are then certified by Homeless Link, which is funded by MHCLG to provide independent verification, validation and guidance to local authorities for the annual rough sleeping count and estimate process.</p><p>We cannot provide any more detailed information about who has submitted their rough sleeping count or estimates during the process, as this could undermine the trust, quality and value of the official statistics.</p><p>As in previous years, the official rough sleeping statistics will be published in January 2019.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-06T10:47:10.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997767/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997767/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities have to date submitted a rough sleeping count for 2018 using the DELTA online system.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997768","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-05","<p>There are specific markers used within DWP Working Age Directorate systems that identify where a customer has declared a mental health condition or requires additional support. The marker information will help to target support where it is most needed, keep all staff informed in transferring information and reduce the need to obtain this information again. These markers are tracked through the customer’s journey to ensure safeguarding procedures are followed, but we do not record and report data on these cases against any measurable success criteria. This is currently being reviewed by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-11-05T17:11:53.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997768/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997768/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-30","Social Security Benefits: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 26 October 2018 to Question 182841 on Social Security Benefits: Mental Health, what metrics her Department is using to measure the success of those safeguards.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","185634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997769","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The government is determined to ensure that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and Living Wage (NMW) receives it. Anyone who feels they have been unpaid NMW should contact the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service (ACAS) helpline on 0300 123 1100 or via the online complaints form at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pay-and-work-rights-complaints" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pay-and-work-rights-complaints</a></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-06T14:56:29.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997769/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997769/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Government Departments: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of SMEs contracted by central government to provide goods and services pay the living wage.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","185522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997770","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-06","<p>All MoJ employees are paid at least the National Minimum Wage and the National Living Wage.</p><p> </p><p>7866 staff employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ HQ, HMCTS, LAA, OPD and CICA) and 6,398 by HMPPS are paid at a rate below £10.25 per hour.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-11-06T13:33:29.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997770/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997770/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-30","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997771","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>None of the Department's directly employed staff earns less than £10.20 per hour.</p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-11-05T15:56:26.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997771/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997771/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997772","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Government strongly encourages businesses to report poor payment practice and instances of late payment, including late payment through the supply chain, in public sector contracts to the Mystery Shopper service in the Cabinet Office</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-06T16:19:19.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997772/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997772/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Government Departments: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Crown Commercial Service collects data on the payment practices of SMEs holding contracts with central government.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","185523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997773","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) pays over and above the National Living Wage, which was increased to £7.83 per hour in April 2018. The MOD has not formally signed up to the Living Wage Rates of £8.75 (National) and £10.20 (London), as defined by the Living Wage Foundation. In 2015 the then Secretary of State for Defence agreed that all London-based staff should be paid at least the equivalent of the Living Wage Foundation's London Living Wage rate. The MOD continues to pay above that rate.</p><p>As at 31 October 2018, a total of 9,965 MOD civilian staff were paid less than £10.20 per hour, of which a total of 1,757 were paid less than £8.75 per hour.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","185757","2018-11-05T17:07:51.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997773/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997773/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-30","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997774","Home Office","false","2018-12-21","<p>From April 2018, all employers in the UK were required to pay a new National Living Wage of £7.83 per hour. The Home Office pays all direct employees at least the statutory National Living Wage, regardless of age.</p><p>There are 987 direct employees of the Home Office who earn less than £8.75 per hour. This includes 103 apprentices and 884 staff on the National and London Provincial pay rates. No employees on the London Pay Rates receive less than £10.20 per hour.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-12-21T16:44:26.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997774/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997774/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Home Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997775","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-05","<p>There have been no specific discussions. Officials are monitoring the situation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-05T11:39:01.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997775/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997775/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-30","Central America: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her (a) US and (b) Mexican counterparts on the provision of aid for migrants travelling north from Central America through Mexico.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","185495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997776","Treasury","false","2018-11-07","<p>Less than five members of staff are paid less than £10.20 per hour in HM Treasury. These employees are based outside of London.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-11-07T16:32:55.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997776/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997776/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997777","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-02","<p>111 UK-Based staff employed by the Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office are paid less than the London Living Wage rate of £10.20 per hour. However, all staff employed within Inner or Greater London receive at least this rate.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-02T16:35:24.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997777/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997777/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997778","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Department operates different pay rates for staff based in London and those based elsewhere. On 31st October 2018, eight individuals working in the Department were paid less than £10.20 per hour. All of these individuals were based outside London. All staff in London were paid £10.20 per hour or more.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-06T16:57:34.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997778/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997778/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Department of Health and Social Care: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997779","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions pays all employees at least the statutory National Living Wage of £7.83 per hour, regardless of age.</p><p> </p><p>The Living Wage Foundation advocates employers paying an alternative hourly rate known as the Real Living Wage (RLW) or London Living Wage (LLW). The current London Living Wage is £10.20.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the working hours calculation used by the Living Wage Foundation DWP paid 15,371 employees less than £10.20 per hour as at September 2018. However, of these, only 14 are in London.</p><p> </p><p>Please note this figure excludes employees on long term unpaid breaks, such as carer’s leave.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-07T14:42:46.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997779/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997779/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-30","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff in her Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997780","Department for Transport","false","2018-11-07","<p>The table below shows the number of staff (expressed as a headcount) paid below £10.20 for DfT(c) and its Agencies, as at 31<sup>st</sup> July 2018. The figures provided cover staff in all locations within the UK.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong> <strong>Below £</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfT(c)</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2,551</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driving Vehicle &amp; Standards Agency</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>4,758</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver &amp; Vehicle Licensing Agency</p></td><td><p>1,421</p></td><td><p>6,013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1,134</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle Certification Agency</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>178</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-11-07T16:46:41.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997780/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997780/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-30","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997781","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-07","<p>We launched the Controlling Migration Fund in October 2016, with £100 million available over four years, to provide additional support to local areas that are facing pressure as a result of recent migration. To date we have funded £74 million. The deadline for bids from local authorities for a share of the remaining £26 million in the Fund was 1 October. My officials are assessing the applications that were submitted and successful projects will be announced in the new year. We will consider how best to continue to provide support for areas in response to the impacts of recent migration as part of the next Spending Review.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-11-07T13:56:13.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997781/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997781/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Migration Impacts Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the merits for communities of reinstating the migrant impact fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","185490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997782","Department for International Trade","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for International Trade does not have any UK staff paid less than £10.20 per hour.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-11-07T11:27:10.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997782/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997782/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-10-30","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997783","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-11-07","<p>I can confirm that all staff directly employed by the Department for Exiting the European Union are paid more than £10.20 per hour. All staff are paid above the living wage, as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-11-07T14:37:10.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997783/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997783/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-30","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997784","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-07","<p>There are 56 staff in the Department, based in the National pay region, paid less than £10.20 per hour. There are no staff based in the London pay region paid less than £10.20 per hour.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-11-07T11:38:37.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997784/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997784/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-30","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997785","Department for Education","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Department for Education and its executive agencies do not have any employees who earn less than £8.75 per hour. There are 101 employees based outside of London who earn less than £10.20 per hour.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","185767","2018-11-07T17:28:56.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997785/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997785/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-30","Department for Education: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997786","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-07","<p>No staff in the Department are paid below £10.20 per hour.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-11-07T12:03:16.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997786/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997786/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-30","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997787","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-05","<p>Every member of staff employed by the Department is paid more than £10.20 per hour for their contracted hours.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-11-05T16:33:26.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997787/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997787/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-30","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997788","Cabinet Office","false","2018-11-15","<p>In my Department, no staff working outside London are paid less than UK Living Wage of £8.75 per hour and no staff working in London are paid less than the London Living Wage of £10.20 per hour.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-11-15T09:50:14.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997788/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997788/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-30","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997789","Attorney General","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Attorney General’s Office does not have any staff paid below £10.20 an hour. Figures for the department’s superintended departments are shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>GLD</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>CPS</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SFO</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HMCPSI</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2018-11-07T10:26:42.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997789/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997789/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-10-30","Attorney General: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many staff in his Department are paid less than £10.20 per hour.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","185791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997790","Home Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>Border Force will always ensure it has the necessary resources to keep the border secure and will respond flexibly to emerging requirements through ongoing assessments of operational needs.</p><p>Border Force has recruited a Readiness Task Force to provide operational resilience to the frontline and allow existing staff to undertake EU exit re-lated training. The c.300 multi-disciplinary Border Force officers will be fully deployed by the end of the year.</p><p>An additional c.600 Border Force officers are being recruited in 2018/19 to respond to the new requirements it will face as a result of EU Exit and to provide resilience at key locations.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-05T17:00:05.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997790/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997790/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","UK Border Force: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made on the proposed increase of eight per cent in Border Force operational staff before 29 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","185713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997791","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>HMRC has published Technical Notices covering Customs, Excise and VAT procedures that would apply if no deal is reached and has written to 145,000 traders over the VAT threshold who currently only trade with the EU on no deal arrangements. A Partnership Pack has also been published on GOV.UK, which is designed for business representative groups to support businesses with what they would need to do under a no deal scenario.</p><p>The Government has engaged extensively with key providers of customs broker services to better understand their potential capacity challenges and has announced a package of measures to support the sector to grow, including an investment of £8 million to support broker training and increased automation. Later in the year we intend to provide more information on what people can do should they wish to make preparations for no deal and when they should do this.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-05T17:34:14.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997791/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997791/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","UK Trade with EU: Borders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the National Audit Office report entitled The UK border: preparedness for EU exit, published on 24 October 2018, what support the Government plans to provide to the estimated up to 250,000 traders who will be required to make border declarations for the first time after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","185714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997792","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Department does not hold this information. It is the responsibility of each local authority to make arrangements and provide for their own Severe Weather Emergency Protocol arrangements according to their local weather conditions and needs. Guidance on the operation of SWEP is available at – <a href="https://www.homeless.org.uk/our-work/resources/guidance-on-severe-weather-emergency-protocol-swep-and-extended-weather-provision" target="_blank">https://www.homeless.org.uk/our-work/resources/guidance-on-severe-weather-emergency-protocol-swep-and-extended-weather-provision</a></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","185509","2018-11-05T15:54:53.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997792/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997792/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many councils implemented Severe Weather Emergency Protocol provision in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997793","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Department does not hold this information. It is the responsibility of each local authority to make arrangements and provide for their own Severe Weather Emergency Protocol arrangements according to their local weather conditions and needs. Guidance on the operation of SWEP is available at – <a href="https://www.homeless.org.uk/our-work/resources/guidance-on-severe-weather-emergency-protocol-swep-and-extended-weather-provision" target="_blank">https://www.homeless.org.uk/our-work/resources/guidance-on-severe-weather-emergency-protocol-swep-and-extended-weather-provision</a></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","185508","2018-11-05T15:54:53.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997793/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997793/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the cost to councils of implementing Severe Weather Emergency Protocol provision in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997794","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>All 12 critical IT systems set out in the National Audit Office report undergo significant scrutiny across government – including at a departmental level, by the Infrastructure and Projects Authority and by the Borders Delivery Group. Where programme risks exist, appropriate mitigation and contingency plans are in place. There is also significant cross-departmental working to ensure that the interdependencies between border systems and wider departmental policy is effectively managed.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-05T17:30:38.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997794/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997794/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","Borders: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the National Audit Office report entitled The UK border: preparedness for EU exit, published on 24 October 2018, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of the finding in that report that 11 out of 12 new or replacement border systems were at risk of not being delivered on time and to acceptable quality by 29 March 2018.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","185715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997795","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>HMRC has well-developed plans to ensure that on day one of a no deal scenario there will be a functioning customs, VAT and excise system.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is already having extensive engagement with ports, airports and rail terminals on what would need to be in place at March 2019 and in the longer term. We are currently developing specific requirements around the physical infrastructure needed in each of the exit scenarios. In a no deal scenario, HMRC’s plans will allow for the border to operate without new infrastructure on day 1, and it is not placing new requirements on ports and airports to have infrastructure in place by day 1.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-11-05T17:11:11.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997795/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997795/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","UK Trade with EU: Borders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress his Department has made on developing the necessary (a) border infrastructure and (b) alternative customs systems needed in the case of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","185716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997796","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Department and entities within its accounting boundary report on the basis of European Union Adopted International Financial Reporting Standards as interpreted and adapted for the public sector by HM Treasury’s Financial Reporting Manual (FReM).</p><p> </p><p>Debt is not a specific classification of liability that is reported by entities including National Health Service trusts.</p><p> </p><p>To provide a total liability amount for NHS trusts, either current and payable within 12 months or non-current and due to be settled beyond 12 months from the end of the financial year, would therefore include items which the Department would not expect to be viewed as debt.</p><p> </p><p>For this reason the Department has interpreted the term debt to refer to outstanding balances on loans both with the Department and with Other Entities. The attached table identifies the total level of loans outstanding for NHS trusts as at 31 March 2018, on a current and non-current basis. As the question specifically refers to NHS trusts, detail for NHS foundation trusts has been omitted.</p><p> </p><p>Loans held with the Department are eliminated on consolidation to arrive at the Group’s Consolidated Statement of Financial Position. As part of presenting a consolidated set of accounts, all intra group activity (including income, expenditure, assets and liabilities generated by intra group trading) is eliminated, so as to not overstate the Group position. For individual NHS trusts these loans with the Department represent a debt but this is not the case in regards to the Group position presented in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts as balances held and transactions related to the loans held are eliminated.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-05T16:45:39.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997796/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997796/answer","PQ185717 Table NHS trust Debt.docx","PQ185717 Table NHS trust Debt.docx","PQ185717 attached table","PQ185717 attached table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997796/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","NHS Trusts: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimates his Department has made of the outstanding debts of NHS trusts in (a) Dulwich and West Norwood, (b) Greater London and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","185717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997797","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is in the process of developing a five year cross sectoral action plan for reproductive health. The action plan will be divided into the themes of reproductive choice (choosing if when and how to become pregnant) and reproductive wellbeing. Menstrual issues, including stigma surrounding heavy menstrual bleeding will be a focus of the strategy, specifically with regards to effective information and communication and workforce training.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is aligning the work with the recently published Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP) publications on guidance for menstrual wellbeing. The guidance is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.rcgp.org.uk/menstrualwellbeingtoolkit" target="_blank">http://www.rcgp.org.uk/menstrualwellbeingtoolkit</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-05T16:37:08.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997797/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997797/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Health: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he plans to take to develop a cross-departmental strategy on menstrual health management to tackle the stigma of periods.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","185614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997798","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Government is committed to maintaining and boosting supply of supported housing. Following our commitment earlier this summer to undertake a review of housing-related support, we are now in the process of finalising the procurement arrangements to enable us to tender the review by the end of the year.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-05T15:51:05.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997798/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997798/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what progress he has made on the promised review of housing related support.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997799","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>Government believes keeping the funding for all supported housing in Housing Benefit, alongside an oversight scheme, will give confidence to the sector and will help us meet our aims of promoting supply, and achieving value for money and positive outcomes for supported housing residents.</p><p>Since the announcement in August to maintain Housing Benefit to fund all supported housing, Government has been working closely with the sector including other representative bodies and local authorities to develop options for oversight of supported housing.</p><p>We have already met a wide range of stakeholders, including local authorities and providers of supported housing and subsequent engagement is planned in the month of November.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-06T10:55:32.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997799/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997799/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what progress he has made on the work with providers, local authorities, membership bodies and resident representatives to develop a robust oversight regime for supported accommodation, announced on 9 August 2018.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997800","Wales Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>I have frequent discussions with the Chief Secretary to the Treasury on a wide range of issues. I was pleased that the Chancellor was able to announce at Budget a review of the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing powers to consider whether the borrowing cap should be increased by up to £300m to support this vital project.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2018-11-05T15:23:38.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997800/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997800/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-10-30","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Chief Secretary to the Treasury on representations received by the UK Government from the Welsh Government on increasing borrowing capacity to fund the M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","185561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997801","Wales Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>I have regular discussions with the Welsh Government on a wide range of issues. The Welsh Government requested an extension to their borrowing powers to fund the M4 and I was pleased that the Chancellor was able to announce at Budget a review of the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing powers to consider whether the borrowing cap should be increased by up to £300m to support this vital project.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2018-11-05T15:24:40.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997801/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997801/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-10-30","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on increasing borrowing capacity for the Welsh Government specifically to fund the M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","185562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997802","Wales Office","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Welsh’s Government’s Cabinet Secretary for Finance wrote on 26th April to request an increase in borrowing capacity, including for the M4 project. I note that the Welsh Government has now published this letter, and I will place a copy in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p><p>Following a dialogue between the UK and Welsh Governments in the intervening period, I was pleased that the Chancellor was able to announce at Budget a review of the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing powers to consider whether the borrowing cap should be increased by up to £300m to support this vital project.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2018-11-05T17:29:27.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997802/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997802/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-10-30","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will publish all communications between the Wales Office and the Welsh Government on increasing borrowing capacity to fund the M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","185563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997803","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Welsh Government Cabinet Secretary for Finance recently wrote to me setting out his intention to see an increase in the Welsh Government’s borrowing limits at the Spending Review to deliver investment priorities in Wales, including the M4 project.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget, we announced that the government will support the delivery of a new M4 relief road through a review of the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing powers at the Spending Review, to consider whether the borrowing cap should be increased by up to £300 million to support this vital project.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","185565","2018-11-05T15:12:00.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997803/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997803/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on increasing borrowing capacity to fund the M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","185564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997804","Treasury","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Welsh Government Cabinet Secretary for Finance recently wrote to me setting out his intention to see an increase in the Welsh Government’s borrowing limits at the Spending Review to deliver investment priorities in Wales, including the M4 project.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget, we announced that the government will support the delivery of a new M4 relief road through a review of the Welsh Government’s capital borrowing powers at the Spending Review, to consider whether the borrowing cap should be increased by up to £300 million to support this vital project.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","185564","2018-11-05T15:12:00.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997804/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997804/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-30","M4: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish all communications between his Department and the Welsh Government on increasing borrowing capacity to fund the M4 relief road.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","185565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997805","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-05","<p>We are deeply concerned that Bangladesh and Burma have announced that they plan to begin repatriation of the Rohingya to Burma in mid-November. We agree with the UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) that the conditions for returns do not yet exist. The UK continues to raise our concerns at the highest levels with both military and civilian Ministers in the Government of Burma. The UK and the UN Security Council have been clear, we want both Burma and Bangladesh to take solid and constructive steps to create the conditions that will allow the Rohingya to return safely, voluntarily and with dignity to Rakhine state. The Rohingya need to be well-informed about the situation they may return to, and there needs to be independent international monitoring of any returns.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2018-11-05T11:45:22.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997805/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997805/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-30","Rohingya: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the recent announcement from the governments of Myanmar and Bangladesh that Rohingya refugees will start to be returned from Bangladesh in November 2018, what assurances her Department has sought from the Government of Myanmar on ensuring that conditions are safe for the Rohingya people to return to Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","185718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997806","Department for Education","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Government is proposing to introduce compulsory Health Education, alongside Relationships Education and Relationships and Sex Education, and is currently consulting on draft regulations and draft statutory guidance on the subjects. Under the topic of physical health and fitness, the draft guidance specifies that pupils should know the facts about wider issues, using organ and blood donation as examples. The Department is considering feedback, including on teaching about stem cell donation, through the consultation process and may revise the guidance as appropriate. The consultation closes on 7 November 2018.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","185616","2018-11-05T11:05:25.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997806/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997806/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-30","Health Education: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he plans to take to improve secondary school pupils' understanding of (a) organ, (b) blood and (c) stem cell donation.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","185615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997807","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>Our Housing White Paper sets out a long term and comprehensive strategy, with dozens of proposals to release more land for homes where people want to live; build the homes we need faster; get more people building homes; and support people who need help now.</p><p>Since then, we have continued to take action to make our housing market work better, including:</p><ul><li><p>Planning reforms to ensure more land is available for housing and maximise the potential of our cities and towns to build new homes whilst protecting the Green Belt;</p></li><li><p>Launching Homes England, bringing together money, expertise, planning and compulsory purchase powers;</p></li><li><p>Lifting Housing Revenue Account borrowing caps so local authorities can deliver a new generation of council housing;</p></li><li><p>More than £15 billion of new financial support over the next five years, taking total financial support to at least £44 billion to 2022/2023. This will boost the delivery of housing and use funds flexibly to unblock the barriers to more housebuilding;</p></li><li><p>Publishing a Green Paper which sets out a new deal for social housing in England;</p></li><li><p>Measures to rebalance the relationship between tenants and landlords to deliver a fairer, good quality and more affordable private rented sector;</p></li><li><p>And reforms to make sure the leasehold system in England is fair and transparent to the consumer.</p></li></ul><p>Taken together, our reforms put us on track to create, fund and drive a fairer housing market that delivers 300,000 homes a year on average by the mid-2020s.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-05T15:53:22.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997807/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997807/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many proposals in the Government's 2017 Housing White Paper (a) were made and (b) have been implemented.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997808","Department for Education","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Government is proposing to introduce compulsory Health Education, alongside Relationships Education and Relationships and Sex Education, and is currently consulting on draft regulations and draft statutory guidance on the subjects. Under the topic of physical health and fitness, the draft guidance specifies that pupils should know the facts about wider issues, using organ and blood donation as examples. The Department is considering feedback, including on teaching about stem cell donation, through the consultation process and may revise the guidance as appropriate. The consultation closes on 7 November 2018.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","185615","2018-11-05T11:05:25.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997808/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997808/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-30","Health Education: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons stem cell donation is not included alongside organ and blood donation in the Government's draft statutory guidance on health education for secondary school pupils.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","185616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997809","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>NHS England is working with the manufacturers and NHS providers to prepare the National Health Service to begin delivering Chimeric Antigen Receptor T Cell (CAR-T) therapy - the first in a wave of treatments in a new era of personalised medicine and part of the NHS’s long-term plan to upgrade cancer service. The first treatment that will be available to patient is tisagenlecleucel (Kymriah) as an option for treating children and young people up to 25 years old with B cell acute lymphoblastic leukaemia that is refractory, in relapsed post-transplant or in second or later relapse.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England anticipates that the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence will recommend this treatment for entry into the Cancer Drugs Fund in mid-November. If so, funding will be made immediately available, following a successful commercial deal with the manufacturer Novartis. We anticipate the first patients will begin their treatment in late November 2018. The phased implementation required by the manufacturer and the NHS means that full capacity to treat eligible patients will take some months to achieve and a National CAR-T Clinical Panel will convene in mid-November to assure equity of access and prioritise eligible patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-05T11:11:35.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997809/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997809/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Haematological Cancer: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what progress has been made on preparing hospitals in England to deliver CAR-T cell therapies for patients with blood cancer.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","185617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997810","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>We are aware of reports that allege that a process of involuntary organ removal may be taking place in China, including suggestions that minority and religious groups are being specifically targeted. The UK government fully supports the Declaration of Istanbul (May 2008), which encourages all countries to draw up legal and professional frameworks to govern organ donation and transplantation activities.</p><p>We consider the Kilgour, Gutmann and Matas report to be important sources of information about China’s organ transplant system. These reports rightly question the lack of transparency in China’s organ transplant system, whilst acknowledging that it is very difficult to identify the source of those organs and verify the number of organ transplants conducted in China. We do not agree with the claims of systematic organ harvesting of prisoners of conscience, assessing that the evidence they present does not substantiate such a claim.</p><p>The World Health Organisation (WHO) collates global data on organ donations and works with China. The WHO view is that China is implementing an ethical, voluntary organ transplant system in accordance with international standards, although the WHO does have concerns about overall transparency.</p><p>We continue to review any new evidence that is presented to us.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-06T11:33:41.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997810/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997810/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","China: Organs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the merits of the evidence collected by former Canadian Minister David Kilgour on forced organ harvesting in China.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","185605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997811","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-06","<p>In February 2018, we announced the successful Housing Infrastructure Fund projects to be funded through Marginal Viability Funding. In March 2018, we announced that we were working with 45 places through Forward Funding.</p><p>The first of the successful Forward Funding projects, to provide £291 million in funding to unlock up to 18,000 homes in East London through improvements to the Docklands Light Railway, was announced at Autumn Budget.</p><p>At Autumn Budget we also announced that the Housing Infrastructure Fund will increase by £500 million to a total of £5.5 billion, unlocking up to 650,000 new homes.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-11-06T10:46:17.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997811/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997811/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-30","Housing Infrastructure Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what projects have been funded by the Housing Infrastructure Fund to date.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","185513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997812","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-05","<p>End of life care is an important part of the proposals which are helping to shape the long-term plan for the National Health Service. The Children’s Hospice Grant is being considered as part of this. NHS England will continue working with key stakeholders to test the plan before its publication later this autumn.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-05T11:05:42.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997812/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997812/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Hospices: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 29 October 2018 to Question 183299 on Hospices: Children, what the value of the NHS England Children’s Hospice Grant will be in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","185549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997813","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>We are aware of reports that allege that a process of involuntary organ removal may be taking place in China, including suggestions that minority and religious groups are being specifically targeted. The UK government fully supports the Declaration of Istanbul (May 2008), which encourages all countries to draw up legal and professional frameworks to govern organ donation and transplantation activities.</p><p>As the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Minister for Europe and the Americas, Sir Alan Duncan, stated in a Westminster Hall debate in October 2016: “Although I do not doubt the need to maintain close scrutiny of organ transplant practices in China, we believe that the evidence base is not sufficiently strong to substantiate claims about the systematic harvesting of organs from minority groups. Indeed, based on all the evidence available to us, we cannot conclude that this practice of “organ harvesting” is definitely happening in China.”</p><p>The World Health Organisation (WHO) collates global data on organ donations and works with China. The WHO view is that China is implementing an ethical, voluntary organ transplant system in accordance with international standards, although the WHO does have concerns about overall transparency.</p><p>We continue to review any new evidence that is presented to us.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-11-06T11:55:47.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997813/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997813/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","China: Organs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the merits of the conclusions of the people's independent tribunal on forced organ harvesting in China.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","185606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997814","Department for International Development","false","2018-11-06","<p>To help address the humanitarian situation in Gaza and alleviate the burdened health system, the UK has provided £1.5 million to the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) Appeal. This will help treat patients in 11 hospitals under pressure in Gaza, by restocking vital medical supplies including surgical equipment, bandages and medical supplies, and to help provide physical rehabilitation services for around 4,000 people, following the recent surge in violence. To help disabled people regain mobility the ICRC will also continue to support the Artificial Limb Centre in Gaza. In addition, the UK has increased its assistance to the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees by an extra £17m this year to help support the provision of basic healthcare in 22 health centres in Gaza.</p><p>Our support in the longer term looks to address the underlying causes of humanitarian strife and raise living standards by focussing on increasing trade and job creation, enabling greater movement and access for people and goods, and enhancing the supply of electricity and clean water. We continue to regularly press the Government of Israel and the Palestinian Authority about the need to expedite medical permits and the unimpeded passage of medical personnel.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-06T15:29:53.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997814/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997814/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-30","Gaza: Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to hospitals in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Bill Grant","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Bill Grant","185730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997815","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-11-06","<p>Since that date, the Minister for Sport and Civil Society spoke to Martin Glenn, the Chief Executive of the Football Association. The Government has been clear all along that any proposed sale of the stadium was a commercial matter between The FA and Mr Khan and we respect Mr Khan's decision to withdraw his bid. I am confident Wembley will continue to thrive with the FA as its custodians.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2018-11-06T18:37:53.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997815/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997815/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-30","Wembley Stadium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had and with whom on the proposed sale of Wembley Stadium since 13 September 2018.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","185569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997816","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>​We strongly condemn all acts of terrorism and call upon Hamas and other terrorist groups to permanently end their incitement and rocket fire against Israel. The UK proscribes Hamas’ military wing and continues to abide by a no-contact policy with Hamas in its entirety. We expect Hamas to adhere to the Quartet Principles, including a commitment to non-violence.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-11-06T17:46:35.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997816/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997816/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","Israel: Hamas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken with international partners to help stem violence against Israel by Hamas.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","185536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997817","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>On 23 August 2018, the Department wrote to a number of pharmaceutical companies that supply the United Kingdom with medicines from, or via, the European Union/European Economic Area, asking them to ensure they have a minimum of six weeks’ additional supply in the UK, over and above their business as usual operational buffer stocks, by 29 March 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, we have received very good engagement from industry who share our aims of ensuring continuity of medicines supply for patients is maintained and able to cope with any potential delays at the border that may arise in the short term in the event of a no-deal Brexit.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-06T11:07:57.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997817/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997817/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-30","Technetium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what preparations his Department has made to ensure that there is a steady supply of Technetium-99m after the UK's leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","185721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997818","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-11-02","<p>We provided consular support to the family of a British couple who died in the flooding overnight on 9-10 October and offered support to the family of a dual national British-Spanish boy whose body was found the following week. We remained in close contact with Spanish authorities throughout this ordeal, including the Regional Government Crisis Centre. We updated FCO Travel Advice for Spain on the morning of 10 October, highlighting the localised impact of the flooding, directing British nationals in affected areas to follow advice from local authorities and publicising our contact details for any other affected British nationals in need of consular assistance. As always, this update was shared through our established social media channels.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-11-02T16:31:45.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997818/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997818/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-30","Spain: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assistance and advice was offered by the Government to UK nationals in Majorca following the recent flooding.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","185537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997819","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-11-02","<p>I do not have a role in setting the Equality Commission for Northern Ireland’s budget or monitoring the spend on legal proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for the Equality Commission’s functions and powers is devolved; it is sponsored by the Executive Office in Northern Ireland, which approves its budget.</p><p> </p><p>As the Commission operates independently from Government you may wish to write directly to the Commission’s Chief Executive, and Accounting Officer, on the matters relating to the use of resources.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2018-11-02T11:11:43.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997819/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997819/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-10-30","Equality Commission for Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the Equality Commission for Northern Ireland's budget was in each of the last five years; and how much was spent in each year on legal proceedings.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","185538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997820","Home Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>The Government recognises the valuable contribution that overseas workers make to the UK economy and to our society. We are currently developing options for the future system which will be designed to work in the national interest.</p><p>On the 18 September, the Migration Advisory Committee published their final report on the current patterns of EEA migration into the UK. We are carefully considering their fourteen recommendations. We plan to publish a White Paper setting out more detail on the future arrangements later in the Autumn.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-07T14:44:31.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997820/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997820/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Agriculture: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what agri-food related occupations will be eligible under the Migration Advisory Committee's recommendations to expand Tier 2 migrant access after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","185539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997821","Home Office","false","2018-11-07","<p>In 2015 the Home Office established the Undercover Policing Inquiry to investigate and report on undercover police operations conducted by English and Welsh police forces in England since 1968. The Home Office is a core participant in the Inquiry and is in the process of disclosing material relevant to its terms of reference.</p><p>The Newham Monitoring Project and the Metropolitan Police are also core participants in the Inquiry. The Inquiry’s investigations are live and ongoing and it would therefore not be appropriate for the Government to comment further. The Inquiry’s approach and plans to report are set out in its strategic review, which was published in May 2018.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","185554 ; 185555 ; 185556","2018-11-07T15:29:40.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997821/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-30","Newham Monitoring Project: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information his Department holds on covert police (a) surveillance and (b) infiltration of the Newham Monitoring Project.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","185553"
